<HEAD>Nina, Pinta, Santa Maria Back In Port After Storm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUELVA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON> could have told them
it wouldn't be easy.
   Ninety Spaniards sailing in exact replicas of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' three
ships, the <ORGANIZATION>Nina</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Pinta</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>, departed from this
southwestern <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> port <DATE>Friday</DATE> on a six-month <LOCATION>Mediterranean</LOCATION> sea
trial.
   But by <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, the explorers, who are preparing for a planned
<DATE>1992</DATE> re-creation of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' voyage to the New World, found
themselves back in port after they were blown to land by a
windstorm.
   Undaunted, <ORGANIZATION>Spanish navy</ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON>Santiago Bolivar</PERSON>, the leader of
the mission, told reporters <DATE>Saturday</DATE>: ``We're going to wait out the
winds before starting out again for our first destination.'' That
destination is <LOCATION>Almeria</LOCATION>, a southwestern Spanish port roughly 310
miles east of <LOCATION>Huelva</LOCATION>.
   The ships' joyful sendoff <DATE>Friday</DATE> coincided with the 498th
anniversary of the day <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> began his first voyage to what
would become known as <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, which bankrolled <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, spent <MONEY>$2 million</MONEY> to build the
three ships from Galician pine and oak from the <LOCATION>Pyrenees</LOCATION>.
   The ships were built to help promote the Expo '92 World's Fair
in the southern city of <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> and to commemorate the 500th
anniversary of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' legendary voyage.
   Expo '92 is expected to attract 20 million visitors to <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>
from <DATE>April</DATE> to <DATE>October 1992</DATE>.
   While the sailors will attempt to follow the exact sailing
methods of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and his intrepid men, the ships are equipped
with sophisticated equipment to navigate via satellite and carry
modern-day lighting.
</TEXT>
