<DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; SERIES; WORLD; US; HISTORY; MAN; DATE; CEREMONY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  COLUMBUS? Columbus who?;    This is the wrong town to mention that name in.
Palos de la Frontera, you see, got the royal shaft from Ferdinand and
Isabella, Columbus -- and history.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WRONG GUY GOT GLORY, SPANISH VILLAGERS INSIST  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Great Columbus Chase
Second in a four-part series  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Up on a wall next to the <ORGANIZATION>Church of St. George</ORGANIZATION> in this small, sunny town in
southwestern <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> is this bold proclamation, set in blue tile:;    "Oh,
Palos! Your glory cannot be equaled. Not even <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION>. Not even <LOCATION>Thebes</LOCATION>. Not
even immortal <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>. Not even <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION>. Not even <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. No city can dispute your
historical fame!";    After all that puffy back-patting, it was natural the
citizenry would throw up a statue or two to commemorate their self-designated
place in history, and indeed, they did.;    So, there is a statue here of the
man who discovered <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>, but it ain't that Italian upstart, Cristobol
Colon. Nope, it's a statue of  <PERSON>Martin Alonso Pinzon</PERSON>, captain of the Pinta
(yeah, that Pinta) and a hometown boy who, they tell you in these parts, made
good but never got the credit.;    And on a brilliant whitewashed house next
to the old church is a colorful portrait, also in tile, of <PERSON>Vicente Yanez
Pinzon</PERSON>, <PERSON>Martin Alonso</PERSON>'s kid brother and the captain of the <PERSON>Nina</PERSON> (yeah, that
Nina). The folks in Palos say that <PERSON>Vicente</PERSON>, who was made captain-general and
corregidor (head of state) of <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>, also discovered <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> and the
mouth of the <LOCATION>Amazon River.</LOCATION>;    Palos and the <ORGANIZATION>Church of St. George</ORGANIZATION> were central
in the saga of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> voyage.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, after years of hanging
around the court of Isabella and Ferdinand, finally got the two sovereigns to
back his trip. But, never a couple to spend a peseta unnecessarily, the royal
pair decided on a little end-around run.;    The sailors of Palos -- including
the Pinzons -- had long experience at sea, trading in <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Azores</LOCATION>.
Right after they promised <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> three ships, the king and queen dug up an
old case involving some African goods imported to Palos without royal duty
being paid.;    The fine for this forgotten infraction was -- guess what --
two ships, ready to sail and loaded with enough stuff to last a year. (Why pay
for three ships, they figured, when we can stiff the good people of Palos for
two of them? Were these two good, or what?);    The taxpayers of Palos were
thus forced to pay for their part in history. The two ships in question were,
of course, the <ORGANIZATION>Nina</ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION>. You can guess how popular <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was when
he arrived in town with that news. The royal order was issued in <DATE>May</DATE> -- and
somehow, the ships were provisioned and ready for sea by August.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
and the elder <PERSON>Pinzon</PERSON> had known each other off and on for years. Near Palos is
the monastery of La Rabida, where <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> spent several years plotting how to
get Ferdinand and Isabella to give him an ear, and some historians say <PERSON>Martin
Alonso</PERSON> was in on the planning.;    And it seems unlikely that without <PERSON>Pinzon</PERSON>
going to bat for him, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> would ever have convinced the neighborhood
sailors to wander off toward the edge of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> -- especially with a
foreigner.;    And it's pretty obvious, looking back, that <PERSON>Palos</PERSON> and other
nearby villages were part of the scheme from the start. The Pinzons and dozens
of other experienced sailors were on tap, the <LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Nina</LOCATION> were already
there and the town was well placed on a little backwater on the <ORGANIZATION>Rio Tinto</ORGANIZATION>, a
wide river that opens into the sea a few miles from town.;    Relationship
turns icy;    On the night of <DATE>Aug. 2, 1492</DATE>, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, the Pinzons and the rest
of the crews went to the <ORGANIZATION>Church of St. George</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Palos</LOCATION> for Mass, then filed
down a set of stairs next to the church to where the three ships were
anchored, and boarded. They sailed the next morning.;    There's little left
today of the anchorage. The small arm of water that connected Palos to the <LOCATION>Rio
Tinto</LOCATION> is long-since silted up, and the only evidence that a wharf ever existed
is a memorial marker and a bit of stone wall.;    It was after the three ships
arrived in the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION> that things apparently got fairly icy between
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Martin Alonso</PERSON>. One historian says <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was constantly afraid
that <PERSON>Pinzon</PERSON> would discover gold before he did (the <LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION> sailed a good deal
faster than the tubby <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>). And toward the middle of their exploration
of <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION> -- and <PERSON>Pinzon</PERSON> -- disappeared for two months. Desertion?
Miscalculation? Gold fever? Who knows?;    Reneging on a deal;    The <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
fleet, minus the <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>, which hit a reef on <ORGANIZATION>Christmas Day</ORGANIZATION>, returned to
Palos in triumph in <DATE>March 1493</DATE>. There were, by all reports, huge parties.
<PERSON>Martin Alonso Pinzon</PERSON> did not attend. Five days after he returned to <LOCATION>Palos</LOCATION>, he
died.;    In later years, <PERSON>Isabella</PERSON> and Ferdinand tried to renege on pre-voyage
payment deals they had made with <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>. One of the strategies they used was
trying to prove that the whole idea -- sailing west to the Indies -- was the
brainchild of <PERSON>Martin Alonso Pinzon</PERSON> and his family. This started suits and
counter-suits that went on for centuries.;    It also created the stubborn
pride of the people of Palos, who for five centuries have said the wrong man
got the credit. Italian author <PERSON>Gianni Granzotto</PERSON>, in his rather biased <DATE>1984</DATE>
biography of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, suggests that the statue of <PERSON>Martin Alonso</PERSON> is
chauvinistic and "clouds the issue.";    "Fame does not make mistakes," he
writes. "Five centuries after the fact, the name of <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON> still
resounds throughout the world. . . . How many people have heard of Pinzon?
Time has buried him, swallowed him up. . . . There (is) a great distance
between him and <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, the distance between obscurity and glory.";    So in
the end <PERSON>Martin Alonso</PERSON> lost. Not only did he die before the full impact of the
voyage was realized, but he also disappeared into history, just a footnote to
the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> myth. Except, of course, in Palos de la Frontera, whose "glory
cannot be equaled.";    The best thing now that can be said for Palos is that
it's close to the Portuguese border and the attractions of the Algarve. If
you're passing by this way, say howdy to <PERSON>Martin Alonso</PERSON> and his kid brother,
look at the church, then drive like a bat for the border.;    <DATE>Today</DATE>, <PERSON>Palos</PERSON>
sits in a bowl of pollution from refineries and factories on both sides of the
<ORGANIZATION>Rio Tinto</ORGANIZATION>. There is another refinery on the coast near La Rabida, and <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
would have trouble steering his small ships out to sea because of the haze.
The monastery (which now has a bar and restaurant on the grounds) is, like
almost every other <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> site in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, closed for repairs, but will be
open again in time for the grand celebration next year.;    And if you're
smart, and happen to be in Palos along about <DATE>August of 1992</DATE>, you'll forget all
about <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and the ocean blue and <DATE>1492</DATE> and all that pastafazool -- and
remember who really discovered the <LOCATION>New World.</LOCATION>; NEXT WEEK: <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> returned in
glory to <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION> after his epic first voyage. He wouldn't recognize the
place now -- and probably couldn't even get out of town. Good luck, <DATE>1992</DATE>
Olympics.; If you go. . .; FOR general information about southwestern
<LOCATION>Andalusia</LOCATION> and the Palos de la Frontera region, contact the <ORGANIZATION>Spanish National
Tourist Office</ORGANIZATION>, 8383 <LOCATION>Wilshire Blvd.</LOCATION>, No. 960, <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION> 90211; (213)
658-7188.;    For more information about the <DATE>1492</DATE> voyage in general and the
Columbus/Pinzon saga in specific, try these books:;    (check) "The Conquest
of Paradise" by <ORGANIZATION>Kirkpatrick Sale</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Knopf</ORGANIZATION>, <MONEY>$24.95</MONEY>).;    (check) "Christopher
Columbus" by <PERSON>Gianni Granzotto</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>University of Oklahoma Press</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>1984</DATE>).;   
(check) "Columbus: His Enterprise" by <PERSON>Hans Konig</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>Monthly Review Press</ORGANIZATION>),
<MONEY>$8.95</MONEY>.;    (check) "Admiral of the Open Sea," <PERSON>Samuel Eliot Morison</PERSON> (Little
<PERSON>Brown</PERSON> and Company, <DATE>1949</DATE>).  </TEXT>
