<DESCRIPT>  HISTORY; FOUND; NORTH-AMERICA; FESTIVAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN FOURTEEN-HUNDRED and Ninety-two,;    Columbus sailed the ocean blue.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE GREAT COLUMBUS CHASE
DESPITE DIARIES, MUCH ABOUT MAN REMAINS A
MYSTERY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
See also related stories on P. 1T, 7T, 8T, 9T and 10T of this section
The Great Columbus Chase  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     That much, we know, is true. Somebody named <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON>, or
<PERSON>Cristoforo Colombo</PERSON> (the Italian version) or Cristobal Colon (the Spanish
spelling), did sail from a tiny port in southern <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> on <DATE>Aug. 3, 1492</DATE>, cross
the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>, land somewhere in the <LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION>, then return to spread the word
that a new world awaited those who embraced God, glory and gold.;    His
diaries exist. The logs of his journeys to the Americas exist. We know where
he died and have some idea where he might be buried. We also have some
indication that he was no saint or selfless explorer, as generations of
American school kids have been taught. Indeed, there is evidence to suggest he
was greedy, malicious, conniving and a cheat. (See accompanying article by
<PERSON>Nora Villagran</PERSON>.);    Whatever, <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> is getting very excited about <DATE>1992</DATE> and
the quincentennial of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> voyage. <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION> is holding the <DATE>summer</DATE>
Olympic Games and <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> is holding the <DATE>1992</DATE> Expo. Both events will be
heavily laced with <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> celebrations. <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> is also gearing up for a fete
or two to honor its native son, especially in his home town of Genoa.;    But
the celebrations are not confined to <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. From <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>;
from <LOCATION>Toronto</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, there are events planned all next year to honor the man
who officially (if not factually) discovered <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>, though he's several
parts enigma.;    His legacy is uncertain, his contributions unclear. But he
has left footprints all over Europe.;    Following those footprints adds
little to the truth about the man -- but the footprints do take you to some
interesting spots.;    Over the next several weeks, from <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION>,
from <LOCATION>Granada</LOCATION> to a tiny monastery in the pollution-clouded <LOCATION>Rio Tinto</LOCATION> valley,
we'll chase <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> around his old haunts, 499 years after he stepped aboard
the <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION> and sailed off to immortality.;    One of the big mysteries
about <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> has always been where he was born. The Italians insist he was
born in <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION> about <DATE>1451</DATE>, the son of <LOCATION>Domenico Colombo</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Susanna
Fontanarossa</PERSON>. His father, so one version goes, was a wool merchant and weaver
who caught the eye of the doge of <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION> and was made gatekeeper of the
Olivella Gate.;    Another version has him being a Jew born in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>; another,
that he was non-Jewish, born in <LOCATION>Spain.</LOCATION>;    Or, even, would you believe,
Norwegian? Tor <PERSON>Borch Sannes</PERSON>, a Norwegian researcher of maritime history, says
in a new book that <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was born in the small community of Hyen in
<LOCATION>Nordsfjord</LOCATION> in western <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>. He was named <PERSON>Christopher Bonde</PERSON>, a Norwegian name
meaning "farmer," but called himself <PERSON>Christopher Colon</PERSON> -- after "colonus," the
Latin word for farmer.;    The <PERSON>Bonde</PERSON> family, so this version goes, was
involved with the royal families of <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION> and left <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION> for
<LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION> in the <DATE>15th century</DATE> because of conflicts between the two royal
families.;    The Scandinavians have always been miffed that <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> gets all
the publicity for discovering the <LOCATION>Western Hemisphere</LOCATION>, citing fairly convincing
evidence that Viking sailors explored the New World around the year 1000,
almost 500 years before <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> sailed. (<PERSON>Stephen Birnbaum</PERSON> discusses this
issue, Page 2T.);    Italian historian <PERSON>Gianni Granzotto</PERSON>, in a <DATE>1984</DATE> biography,
says <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> began his sailing career as a boy, perhaps as young as 13,
accompanying wool shipments belonging to his father.;    Off to sea;    In
<DATE>1476</DATE>, according to American historian <PERSON>Samuel Eliot Morison</PERSON>, a Genoese convoy
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was with was attacked by a Franco-Portuguese war fleet of about a
dozen vessels, and <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was wounded in the battle. He escaped his sinking
ship and managed to swim and cling to an oar until he reached the shore of
<LOCATION>Portugal</LOCATION> near <LOCATION>Lagos.</LOCATION>;    He apparently was not taken prisoner, because the
next year he sailed to <LOCATION>Iceland</LOCATION> and then moved back to <LOCATION>Lisbon</LOCATION> to take up work
as a chart maker and sailor.;    <PERSON>Granzotto</PERSON> opines that it was a move of
fateful consequence, because <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION> offered little incentive for
world-exploring voyages. <LOCATION>Portugal</LOCATION>, on the other hand, was by this time a
center for maritime studies, and its explorers were at the forefront of the
epic voyages of discovery.;    After about eight years in <LOCATION>Lisbon</LOCATION>, plus a
marriage and a number of wide-ranging voyages, the saga now has <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
starting his round of visits to the royal courts of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, trying to get
monetary backing for a voyage to discover a western route to <LOCATION>India.</LOCATION>;    Myth
has it that he stood alone in the belief that the world was round, and was
turned down again and again by ignorant nobles unwilling to fight against
traditional geographers.;    In fact, most anybody with an ounce of education
believed by this time that the world was round. What <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> had to sell was
a new route, one that would be cheaper and more efficient than the overland
routes that had been used for centuries, or the new southern ocean route
around the tip of Africa.;    He first went to the king of <LOCATION>Portugal</LOCATION> in <DATE>1483</DATE>.
The king, <PERSON>John II</PERSON>, was one of the many Portuguese monarchs who were ardent and
educated supporters of exploration, but he felt the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> route was too
uncertain.;    Rejected, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> tried next door, in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>. In <DATE>1485</DATE>, he
arrived at <ORGANIZATION>Palos de la Frontera</ORGANIZATION>, a tiny port just across the <ORGANIZATION>Rio Tinto</ORGANIZATION> from
the Portuguese border. Near Palos was the monastery of La Rabida.;    A
devious schemer?;  Those who think <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was a devious schemer believe his
arrival in the area was no quirk. At La Rabida were two prelates, Father
Antonio de <PERSON>Marchena</PERSON> and Father Juan Perez.;    De <PERSON>Marchena</PERSON> was a cosmographer,
a man popular at court and a man not ill at ease with the vision of a round
world. And <PERSON>Perez</PERSON> (the plot thickens) was Queen Isabella's personal confessor.;
   By <DATE>1486</DATE>, thanks to the two clergymen, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> had been presented at court,
but not to the king and queen. Ferdinand and <PERSON>Isabella</PERSON> were busy kicking the
Moors out of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, and the siege of the last major Moorish stronghold,
<LOCATION>Granada</LOCATION>, was under way. Columbus had to wait until the expulsion was complete
-- a wait that lasted six years.;    In <DATE>April 1492</DATE>, the victorious <PERSON>Isabella</PERSON>
met <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> at the small village of <LOCATION>Santa Fe</LOCATION> near <LOCATION>Granada</LOCATION>, one of a series of
meetings the two had over the years. This time, she was ready to support the
scheme.;    But according to <LOCATION>Granzotto</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> made outrageous demands. In
exchange for royal backing, for example, he wanted <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> of all profits
from the new world. He also wanted the title of Admiral of the <ORGANIZATION>Open Ocean</ORGANIZATION>. The
sovereigns eventually agreed, then later reneged on the deal, starting a
series of lawsuits between the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> family and the crown of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> still
not resolved.;    <PERSON>Isabella</PERSON> did not hock her jewels to pay for the trip, by the
way; her husband, <LOCATION>Ferdinand</LOCATION>, had to approve all bills, and in this case, the
money came from the royal treasury, and according to historian <PERSON>Morison</PERSON>, from
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> himself. The cost to obtain and outfit three ships? Morison says
<MONEY>$14,000</MONEY>.;    Because of crowded conditions in other ports, it was decided that
the voyage would commence from <ORGANIZATION>Palos de la Frontera</ORGANIZATION>. Isabella, one of
history's darker figures, was a violent anti-Semite who is given credit for
beginning the Spanish Inquisition and for formulating the <DATE>March 14, 1492</DATE>,
order for the expulsion of all Jews from Spain.;    ecause of that order, many
southern Spanish ports were filled with refugees; the two sovereigns finally
ordered all ships carrying Jewish exiles to leave port by <DATE>Aug. 2</DATE> -- the day
before <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> sailed.;    Land Ho!;  It took the three ships -- the immortal
<ORGANIZATION>Pinta</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Nina</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION> -- more than 40 days to reach the Bahamas
(including a forced layover in the <LOCATION>Azores</LOCATION>). Ferdinand and <PERSON>Isabella</PERSON> had offered
a lifetime annuity to the first man to spy land in the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>. Granzotto
tells us it was Rodrigo de Triana aboard the <ORGANIZATION>Pinta</ORGANIZATION>. At <TIME>2 a.m.</TIME>, <DATE>Oct. 12, 1492</DATE>,
he yelled "Tierra, tierra!" And never got a dime.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> later claimed
that he was the first to spot land. He said the previous evening, <DATE>Oct. 11</DATE>, he
had spotted a candle light on shore. Granzotto, noting that the ships were at
that point about 30 miles offshore, says it would have been impossible to see
the light. "A cruel abuse of power," he calls the action. Columbus kept the
prize.;    <DATE>Oct. 12</DATE> -- <LOCATION>Columbus Day</LOCATION> in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> -- he went ashore at
<LOCATION>San Salvador Island</LOCATION> in the <LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION> and claimed it for <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>. He and his crew
made the first recorded contact between Europeans and the natives of the <LOCATION>New
World</LOCATION> -- in this case, apparently, the Arawak Indians.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> took
several Indians back to <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> with him and presented them at the royal court
in <LOCATION>Barcelona.</LOCATION>;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> made four more voyages to the new lands but
significantly never really recognized that two major land masses were nearby.;
   He explored many of the islands of the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> (and did step ashore in
what is now <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>) but found little gold and no proof at all that he had
discovered a new route to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. His health worsened (he caught malaria, had
gout and arthritis), and worse, the coral and sand islands of his new realm
yielded little that increased his fortunes.;    Royal displeasure;  Ferdinand
and Isabella were less than pleased by these voyages. On one, he lost a whole
fleet. On another, he was forced to deal with a mutiny that eventually saw him
returned to <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> in chains.;    The sovereigns had little to show for their
backing and were more and more reluctant to abide by their contract with
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, especially the part that gave him <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> of all the goodies
(such as they were) coming back from the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>. Then his chief ally,
<LOCATION>Isabella</LOCATION>, died in <DATE>November 1504</DATE>, less than a month after his return from the
last voyage.;    He and <PERSON>Ferdinand</PERSON> fought a prolonged battle over what was owed
to whom, a battle that apparently worsened <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' already frail health (he
was 53 at the time).;    In the <DATE>spring of 1505</DATE>, he moved to <LOCATION>Valladolid</LOCATION> in
northern <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, where he died a year later. He died too soon to realize that
his dream of gold and glory was real, and that the new world was more than
sandy, barren islands in the middle of the ocean. Within 15 years, <PERSON>Hernan
Cortes</PERSON> had defeated the Aztecs and by <DATE>1532</DATE>, <PERSON>Juan Pizarro</PERSON> had taken control of
the Inca empire.;    Whether he was a gold-hungry, greedy con artist who sold
a bill of goods to a couple of naive monarchs, or a great mariner and
courageous explorer, continues to be a historic debate even today, almost five
centuries later.;    If Columbus/Colombo/Colon were around today, he might be
pleased to know his name is still widely known. Or he might just fly off to
<LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> to see <PERSON>King Juan Carlos</PERSON> and check on that <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> he has coming.  </TEXT>
