<CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: On his last trip to the New World in 1502, Christopher
Columbus abandoned two leaking caravels in Jamaica. Marine archaeologists
think they have found the spot, and they hope to dig up the ships.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HISTORY; BOAT; FOUND; JAMAICA  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  When he set sail with four small caravels on his final trip to the New World
in 1502, Christopher Columbus expected to find his long-sought shortcut to
Asia and emerge from the disgrace that less than two years before had seen him
stripped of honors and clapped in chains.;    Instead, with two leaking
caravels already abandoned in Panama after a year of perilous wandering, and
the remaining two no longer seaworthy, the ailing 52-year-old admiral and his
mutinous crew barely made it to the beach in this placid bay on the north
coast of Jamaica.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COLUMBUS SHIPS REPORTEDLY FOUND
TWO VESSELS BELIEVED TO BE IN JAMAICAN BAY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' misfortune -- shipwrecked here for a year and five days only
"a crossbow shot," as his son phrased it, from a band of hostile Arawak
Indians -- may be a boon to <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION> and a team of Texas-based marine
archaeologists. They believe they have found the spot where <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> ran the
two caravels aground 488 years ago.;    "We are <PERCENT>98 percent</PERCENT> sure they are
here," said <PERSON>Dr. James M. Parrent</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Institute of Nautical Archaeology</ORGANIZATION> at
<ORGANIZATION>Texas A&amp;M University</ORGANIZATION>, who, in cooperation with the government of <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION>,
first began looking for the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> caravels in <DATE>1982.</DATE>;    After starting work
in earnest <DATE>last summer</DATE>, <PERSON>Parrent</PERSON> said he hopes soon to unearth the keels and
some of the lower hull planking of the caravels "Capitana" and "<LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> de
Palos" -- all that could be expected to remain after almost five centuries
under the bay's bottom -- for expert study and eventual display in a <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION>
museum.;    "We are charged with locating perhaps the most important historic
archaeological site in the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>," <PERSON>Parrent</PERSON> said, noting that as the
quincentennial of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' first voyage in <DATE>1492</DATE> approaches, no other trace
has been found of the ships he sailed.;    They not only will be the oldest
European vessels discovered in the <LOCATION>Western Hemisphere</LOCATION> and the only ones
actually commanded by <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, he said, they also will help solve a simple
question that has plagued naval architects and historians for centuries,
namely: What did a caravel look like?;    <LOCATION>The Nina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION> -- mainstays of
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' first voyage, the Spanish-underwritten expedition that launched him
into Western lore as the finder of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> -- were fast-sailing caravels that
he preferred over the larger, more lumbering <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>. Yet no reliable
drawing, painting or naval architect's plan of any of the vessels ever has
been found.;    Although divers have uncovered remains of other 16th-century
vessels thought to be similar to those sailed by <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, there remains so
much uncertainty that every attempt to construct replicas, including several
now under way for quincentennial celebrations, has involved guesswork, <PERSON>Parrent</PERSON>
said.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  DON A. SCHANCHE, Los Angeles Times  </BYLINE>
