<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Television:
   Columbus and His Controversial Legacy
   ----
   By Dorothy Rabinowitz
</HL>
<DATE>
10/07/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   Toward the very end of this documentary, a beaming Edward
I. Koch appears -- one of a group of people invited to give
their views on Columbus's legacy. Always a man to get down to
the real significance of events, Mr. Koch, who was then still
mayor of New York, observes, "If Christopher Columbus had not
crossed the seas in 1492, I would never have been the mayor.
Isn't that true?"
   It is a nice moment, the mayor in his old form. Besides,
by this time in the proceedings -- the end of a grandly
conceived, extraordinarily detailed seven-part PBS series --
we are about ready for a laugh. However, neither the National
Council of Churches, nor other Columbus bashers, will find
much to be amused at or to like in "Columbus and the Age of
Discovery," whose first two episodes aired last night.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Try though the film makers did to accommodate all views,
including the current politically correct one, the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
that emerges from this work is unmistakably a heroic figure,
whose achievement and historic legacy are eminently worthy of
celebration. This is not, of course, the view of the <ORGANIZATION>National
Council of Churches</ORGANIZATION>, which recently took occasion to express
its horror at the prospect of the quincentenary celebrations.
In keeping with the advanced political views for which it is
justly famed, the <ORGANIZATION>NCC</ORGANIZATION> declared that <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s arrival in the
<LOCATION>New World</LOCATION> was an occasion for "repentance" not celebration,
since <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s disovery had led to "genocide" as well as
"ecocide" and a host of other crimes against humanity too
numerous to mention here. The European discovery and
settlement of the New World was, in the view of the <ORGANIZATION>National
Council of Churches</ORGANIZATION>, "a historic tragedy."
   In this posture, the <ORGANIZATION>National Council of Churches</ORGANIZATION> is,
needless to say, not alone. The <ORGANIZATION>National Endowment</ORGANIZATION> for the
Humanities, the second largest financial supporter (after
<ORGANIZATION>Xerox</ORGANIZATION>) of "<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and the Age of Discovery," not long ago
refused to fund another film project because of its treatment
of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>. In the opinion of that film maker too, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
was guilty of genocide -- a view, it need hardly be said, now
all the rage among the politically enlightened.
   The current PBS series doesn't neglect the ravages that
the age of discovery brought to the native peoples of the new
land. But neither, to its credit, does it neglect to note the
benefits the Europeans brought to the New World, and also
those they took from it. The most engrossing installment is
"The Columbian Exchange" (named after the <DATE>1972</DATE> book of the
same name, by <PERSON>Alfred W. Crosby</PERSON>, on which it is based). This
segment, which airs tomorrow night as part six, follows the
journey of the potato, of which Europeans were ignorant till
it was brought to their shores from the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>. The
potato, discovered in the <LOCATION>Andes</LOCATION>, became the subsistence crop
that fed and enlarged the population of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. This
impressive episode (the script was written by <PERSON>Graham Chedd</PERSON>)
also delivers a shattering history of the Irish potato
famine. It connects events and consequences, something that
this documentary does, on the whole, very well.
   The potato famine brought the migration from <LOCATION>Ireland</LOCATION> to
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>. African slaves worked and died on the sugar
plantations of the New World. But -- as this production makes
clear -- the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION> also introduced the corn and cassava
that would become the mainstays of the African food supply.
The series (produced by <PERSON>Zvi Dor-Ner</PERSON>) often feels like a
return visit -- a fascinating one to be sure -- to the
gradeschool classroom, where teachers once taught geography
and history and where -- so we are assured -- it is still
taught.
   The series is at its best in this factual mode. On the
other hand, nothing in the script equals the power of the
readings from <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s diary of his voyage: "<DATE>Sunday</DATE>,
<DATE>September 16, 1492</DATE>. Today there were some clouds and it was a
great delight to enjoy the morning. Nothing was lacking but
to hear the nightingales."
   At its worst, the script can get to be like a good part of
tonight's first hour, titled "The Crossing." Here we are
dragged aground, through the Spanish navy's commemoration of
the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> quincentenary. Captains and crews man replicas
of the <ORGANIZATION>Nina</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Pinta</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION> and attempt to retrace
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s first voyage. If there were any justice in the
world, a special place in hell would be reserved for the
person who invented dramatic re-enactments. Granted,
television requires pictures, which this sort of re-creation
can provide, but such pictures come at a high cost to
authenticity. Parts of the re-enactment of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s voyage,
in fact, seem positively unhinged. At one point, a sonorous
voice declares that "many things have changed in 500 years,
but not the pattern of life on a sailing vessel" -- a message
accompanied by footage of a sailor in yuppie athletic togs
doing his situps. Also helping to put us in the historical
mood is the pop vocal blaring from the <LOCATION>Nina</LOCATION> or maybe it's the
<LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION>. In one corner of the deck on which <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s men are
supposed to be sailing, a sailor sits playing "As Time Goes
By" on his trumpet. Yes, we can feel the 15th century all
around us. At another point, we are privileged to see a power
boat draw near one of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> replicas -- and to learn
that it carries one sailor's girlfriend and his parents, on
an outing.
   In short, this production has its flaws. Some are simply
annoyances, such as the repetition of cautious formulations
designed to avoid offending any political side. Columbus is
forever being described as a man who changed the course of
history "for better or for worse" or its equivalents -- of
which there are many. And -- not to be stuffy -- but is it
asking too much of a PBS film into which millions were poured
that its writers have enough of a grasp of English usage to
keep them from producing lines such as the one that informs
us that <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was so rushed, he had no time "to
contemplate the enormity of his journey?"
   Flaws and annoyances aside, this exploration of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
and the New World is a major achievement, a fact that becomes
increasingly evident in the final three hours, which air
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE> and <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> nights. At the end, the film's effort
to maintain an even keel in all political directions finally
yields, as the narrator, with some passion, utters the last
line: "So let us commemorate -- and yes, celebrate
<PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON>." If this portrait is the worst thing to
happen to <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and his legacy in the months to come, we
will have reason to be grateful.
</TEXT>
