<HEAD>Japan To Build Replica Of Santa Maria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> will build a replica of <PERSON>Christopher
Columbus</PERSON>'s ship, the <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>, and sail it from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>
in <DATE>1992</DATE> to mark the 500th anniversary of the explorer's discovery
of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>, an official said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Akihiko Osugi</PERSON>, an official at <ORGANIZATION>Kadokawa Publishing Co.</ORGANIZATION>, said the
plan was announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> by company president <PERSON>Haruki Kadokawa</PERSON>,
who is chairman of the organizing committee.
   Osugi said that at the suggestion of Eikichi Hayashiya, a former
Japanese ambassador to <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Kadokawa</PERSON> and other businessmen,
politicians and scholars decided to fulfill <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' dream of
sailing from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>.
   He said Japanese technicians will build a replica of the
three-mast <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>, used by <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> when he discovered
American in <DATE>1492</DATE>. The replica, to be built in <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>,
will cost <MONEY>$9.85 million</MONEY>, he said.
</TEXT>
