<LEADPARA>  WOULD the world have been a different place if an Indian in a sailing ship
landed in Europe before Christopher Columbus hit the Bahamas? You bet.;  
Maybe the Indians would have colonized Spain instead of vice versa. Maybe
Columbus, Ohio, would have a different name. And maybe we'd all be eating
buffalo meat.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SAIL THE OCEAN BLUE -- VERY, VERY SLOWLY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The New Season; (box) COLUMBUS AND THE AGE OF DISCOVERY; Sunday-Wednesday
nights at 9, Ch. 9;; Monday and following three Monday nights at 9, Ch. 54.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But even those who would rewrite history can't change it, and it was
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> who came west instead of the Indians going east. And that voyage did
set off a chain-reaction of epic events, both good and evil, which affect the
entire globe to this day.;   With the 500th anniversary of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' first
voyage just a year away, the debate over its meaning is about to become a
cottage industry.;   And no cottage industry is complete without a TV show: in
this case <ORGANIZATION>PBS</ORGANIZATION>'s seven-hour "<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and the Age of Discovery," public TV's
attempt to do for the discovery of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> what it did last year for the Civil
War.;   But alas, <PERSON>Zvi Dor-Ner</PERSON>, the film maker who spent 10 years putting
"<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" together, is no <PERSON>Ken Burns</PERSON>, the man behind the magnificent "Civil
War." In <PERSON>Burns</PERSON>' hands these seven hours wouldn't seem so much like 12 or 14.; 
 What "<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" offers are two or three interesting hours about "history's
most stunning accident" -- stretched to seven mostly dull ones. Beautiful, but
dull.;   By the time the series really hits its stride in hour six, I'm afraid
no one will be watching.;   Most people will have a hard time staying with
<DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s opening two hours, which meander around the globe, setting up
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' times, his motivation and his struggle to get someone to finance his
dream of sailing west to reach the <LOCATION>East</LOCATION>. Surely this could have been done in
one hour instead of two.;   Even the prologue is prolonged, as narrator <PERSON>Will
Lyman</PERSON> ("<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>: A Television History") asks, "Should we celebrate <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'
great achievement, or should we mourn a world forever lost?";   The answer, of
course, is both. No matter what horrors followed -- and the decimation of the
native population of Hispaniola from half a million to 500 in little more than
25 years, six of them while <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> himself was governor, certainly is a
horror -- the voyage itself was an astounding achievement of navigation and
courage. We see that chronicled in Part 3, "The Crossing.";   It's what
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> and others did after they landed that's so debatable, substituting
one culture for another and rarely gently.;   The debate is dealt with in
"<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" -- and not just by experts but by real people in the lands
affected. Like everything else here, though, the show takes a long time to get
there.;   If you hang in, however, you will learn something: that <PERSON>Martin
Pinzon</PERSON> is seen as the real hero of the first voyage by many Spaniards; or how
the exchange of crops and animals between the New and Old Worlds put horses on
the American plains, brought potatoes to <LOCATION>Ireland</LOCATION>, corn to <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and sugar
cane to the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>, for example.;   With cane, sadly, came slaves, a far
less noble part of the trade, explored in the series' most successful hour,
the sixth one, called "The <ORGANIZATION>Columbian Exchange</ORGANIZATION>.";   The conclusion, "In Search
of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>," lays out the astounding paradox of the man: "<PERSON>Christopher
Columbus</PERSON>, an Italian seaman sailing for the Catholic monarchies of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, has
been embraced as a national hero by the mainly English-speaking, <ORGANIZATION>Protestant
United States of America</ORGANIZATION> in a land he never set foot in, that he refused to
believe existed and that was named for someone else.";   Had the rest of this
series been as succinct, it would have been a glorious triumph instead of such
a tedious trip.  </TEXT>
