<DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; FESTIVAL; SPAIN; MAN; FOUND; NORTH-AMERICA; HISTORY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  UP ABOVE the door, a wide-screen television is bringing the afternoon
bullfights from Madrid. Big-time razzle-dazzle has made it to la corrida.
Instant replays of the moment of death. Live interviews with the toreros
moments after the triumphant kill. Critical commentary. Death in the afternoon
as designed by Wide World of Sports. Hemingway would not have approved.
Hemingway would have made obnoxious noises. Hemingway is long gone.;    The
dozens of men in the bar -- only a couple of women -- are watching the tube
now and then, drinking tiny cups of strong Spanish coffee, reading newspapers,
talking politics and taxes, doing those things men do in Spanish bars on rainy
afternoons.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOODBYE, COLUMBUS
EVEN HIS BURIAL SPOT IS A SUBJECT OF MUCH
DISPUTE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
The Great Columbus Chase
Last in a four-part series  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION>, facing the Plaza Mayor in the heart of this fairly plain
city on the plains of northern <LOCATION>Andalusia</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION>, busy bar and
social center. The <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION>, last resting place for the Admiral of the
<LOCATION>Open Ocean</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Don Cristobal Colon</PERSON>, the dude who discovered America.;    Or is
it?;    Historians are in general agreement about the final fate of
<PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON>. He made four voyages to the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>, starting in <DATE>1492</DATE>
-- voyages that eventually destroyed his health and soured his soul. His last
years were spent haggling with the king of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> about the profits he had
coming from the discovery of the <LOCATION>Western Hemisphere.</LOCATION>;    When he was given
backing by <PERSON>Ferdinand</PERSON> and Isabella in <DATE>1492</DATE>, he extracted an agreement that
included some major concessions by the crown, including a <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> share of
all profits from the new lands, as well as honorary titles.;    The crown
chose to redefine the agreement toward the end of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' life, taking away
most of his claims. (Despite this, he was quite rich.) He was allowed to keep
his titles -- as were his heirs. Today, there is a Cristobal Colon in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, a
young man who still has the right to be called the Admiral of the Open Sea,
the title  <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> insisted he be given before he took off for the edge of
the world.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> moved to <LOCATION>Valladolid</LOCATION> in <DATE>1506</DATE> and died there <DATE>May 20</DATE>.
That much is sure. What happened after that is the subject of some debate
among scholars.;    One version has him being buried in <LOCATION>Valladolid</LOCATION>, then being
moved to a monastery in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> sometime between <DATE>1509</DATE> and <DATE>1514</DATE>. In <DATE>1537</DATE>, he
was moved to <ORGANIZATION>Santo Domingo</ORGANIZATION> (the Bahamian island where he supposedly landed in
<DATE>1492</DATE>). In <DATE>1795</DATE>, his remains were moved to <LOCATION>Havana</LOCATION>, where they stayed until the
end of the Spanish-American War. They were then sent back to <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> and
buried in the great cathedral there.;     Italian biographer <PERSON>Gianni Granzotto</PERSON>
has the most intriguing the story -- and this is where the <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION> comes
on the scene.;    <PERSON>Granzotto</PERSON> says that on the Plaza Mayor -- right where the
<ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION> sits <DATE>today</DATE> -- there was a Franciscan monastery at the time of
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' death. The monastery, <PERSON>St. Francis</PERSON>, contained a burial crypt.;    The
crypt now lies beneath the floor of the <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Granzotto</PERSON> says it
contains the bones of <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON>, devout Franciscan.;    So it was
no surprise that after the usual tourist inquiry was made -- i.e., where's the
body? -- the owner of the <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION> himself arrived at the table and
allowed there was a chance <PERSON>Don Cristobal Colon</PERSON> was moldering beneath his
feet.;    "Many Americans, many English, they come in here and ask to see his
grave. We do not know that it really is there because that was long ago. But
perhaps, why not? It is an interesting little story, is it not?";    And so
you won't be totally disappointed that no tours of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> bones are
available (or at least offered), he hands out free <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION> calendars as
souvenirs and walks away to discuss the bullfight.;    So, who cares?; 
Goodbye, <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, write if you find work -- or the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>, whatever -- and
don't call us, we'll call you. Valladolid, unlike most of the other European
haunts of the great explorer, seems mostly indifferent to its connection with
Spanish history.;    Yeah, there's a statue of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, but this is no big
deal -- in <LOCATION>Andalusia</LOCATION> and most other parts of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, any town with more than 10
people is likely to have at least one bronze rendering of our Italian hero.;  
 The house in <LOCATION>Valladolid</LOCATION> where he died apparently is gone, but there is a
small museum nearby that once was owned by the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> family and serves as a
symbolic tie to the past. (In some tourism literature, the museum is, in fact,
described as the house where he died.);    But nowhere in the city are there
signs directing the curious to the museum, and it's clear from the patrons of
the <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION> that the exact spot where the Great Explorer dropped his
last anchor is of little importance -- especially on the afternoon of the
<LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> bullfights.;    The museum is closed this year in anticipation of the
500th anniversary of his first voyage next year, and there are some historical
displays going up around the Plaza Mayor.;    In official city maps, which
have illustrated notes about many historical buildings around the city, there
is some mention of the statue honoring "the illustrious Almirante del Mar
Oceano -- Admiral of the Open Ocean," but the location of the museum and house
are given only a single line -- and many locals, when asked, seem not to know
where the house is.;    <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>'s claim;  Most of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> madness around
the vast province of <LOCATION>Andalusia</LOCATION> is centered in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>, site of the <DATE>1992</DATE>
world's fair. The folks in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> have no doubt about the bones -- they are
now, always have been, always will be stashed in the cathedral of <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>.
Valladolid? The <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte</ORGANIZATION>? Nothing but the ramblings of an uninformed
historian -- an Italian one at that.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> used <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> as a base for
several of his later trips to the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>, and it also was from here that
the other Italian explorer -- <PERSON>Amerigo Vespucci</PERSON>, the one with the good press
agent -- sailed. (Two continents were named after <PERSON>Vespucci</PERSON>; <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> got one
American country, one Canadian province and a nice town in <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>.);    The <DATE>1992</DATE>
<ORGANIZATION>Seville Expo</ORGANIZATION> is one of two big deals going on in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> next year, the other
being the <DATE>summer</DATE> Olympic Games in <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION>. And, like <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION>, big chunks
of <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> are torn up in preparation.;    <LOCATION>The Expo</LOCATION>, like the Olympics, is
tied into the 500th anniversary of the first <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> voyage in <DATE>1492</DATE>. The Expo
theme is "The Age of Discovery," and the <ORGANIZATION>Columbus-Seville</ORGANIZATION> connection is being
pushed hard.;    Dem bones, dem bones;  Millions of people are expected to
wander through <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> next <DATE>summer</DATE> to check out the fair and soak up some
<ORGANIZATION>Columbiana</ORGANIZATION>. But the guest of honor won't be around. Seville can make all the
rash claims it wants, and hold all the parties it can, and hire herds of
public relations types to hype the 500th anniversary of the great admiral's
exploits. But everyone knows old <PERSON>Chris</PERSON> is stuck in <LOCATION>Valladolid</LOCATION>, under the floor
of the <ORGANIZATION>Cafe El Norte.</ORGANIZATION>;    We'll leave him there, 500 years and half a
continent away from where he started back in <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION>. One thing about <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
-- you might not admire him much, but you have to admit he got around. And
following in his footsteps around <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> won't make you any better historian,
but it surely will lead you to some great food, nice folks and pretty
scenery.;    It almost makes you want to hop on a leaky old boat and sail off
to the edge of the world.;    Almost.  </TEXT>
