<HEADLINE>  WHY COLUMBUS SAILED OFF FOR SPICES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EX1/5, EX4/4 , WL7
Education
Family Learning
Dr. William F. Russell's books for parents and children include Classic Myths
to Read Aloud.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     We also know that <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was far from alone in believing the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> was
round. It was pretty well taken for granted during his time, although <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
thought the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> was much smaller than the size estimated by most scholars of
the day, and on this point he was dead wrong.;    <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> believed in the
"big <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>, small <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>" theory, and argued that <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> lay just
2,000 miles or so west of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>. Actually, a westward voyage to <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> would
have been at least 10,000 miles long, and had not <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> accidentally bumped
into the New World, he and his crew would surely have died of thirst and never
merited so much as a footnote in our history books.;    WHAT many of our
children don't know about <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, though, is just why he set out on this
perilous voyage in the first place. And it is just this type of inquiry that
can help all of us imbue our children with a "sense" of history, by which I
mean a feeling for the flesh-and-blood human beings that seem so lifeless or
so immortal when they are portrayed in our children's history texts.;    It
takes great imagination to picture oneself as living during the times of
various historic events, but this is just what children must do if they are
ever to see history as being more than a boring collection of facts and dates,
and if they are ever to use the lessons of history to guide their own lives.; 
  Children take refrigerated food and frozen dinners for granted, but can they
imagine what meals must have been like in <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' time, when salt was the
only known preservative and when most foods -- especially meats -- arrived at
the table already spoiled and tasting of decay?;    Perhaps they can
understand then why spices -- especially pepper -- were, quite literally,
worth their weight in gold. Pepper and nutmeg and cloves could mask the awful
taste and smell of spoiled food, but these spices were found only in the <LOCATION>Spice
Islands</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Orient</LOCATION>, and so Europeans had to pay dearly for them to be
transported across Asia.;     <LOCATION>COLUMBUS</LOCATION> convinced the king and queen of <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>
that he could reach these spice-bearing lands from the other direction, and
throughout his life he maintained that he had done just that, refusing to
believe that he had discovered anything new.;    To help your children get
better acquainted with their own senses of smell and taste, make sure they
know that these two senses are related: It is very difficult to taste anything
that you cannot smell. Put a clip on your child's nose and then put a few
grains of fresh ground coffee in his mouth. Can he taste what he is chewing?
Then have him remove the clip and feel the instantaneous rush of flavor that
accompanies the return of his sense of smell.  </TEXT>
