<HEAD>Pilgrims Sailed in the Pinto? Wait a Minute ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How's this for revisionist history? The
pilgrims sailed to <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> in the <LOCATION>Pinto</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Paul Revere</PERSON> wrote ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.'' <PERSON>Sandra Day O'Connor</PERSON> is chief justice of the
<ORGANIZATION>U.S. Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION>.
   And Gen. <PERSON>Douglas MacArthur</PERSON> said, ``Give me liberty or give me
death.'' Or was it <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr.</ORGANIZATION>?
   These are samplings of responses from community-college students
to questions that might be asked of immigrants seeking <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
citizenship.
   Just five of 119 students at <ORGANIZATION>Bellevue Community College</ORGANIZATION> managed
a passing grade of <PERCENT>70 percent</PERCENT> or better.
   ``This is pretty bad,'' said <PERSON>Aslam Khan</PERSON>, head of the college's
political science department, who administered the test.
   ``Why should we give these questions to foreigners when our own
citizens don't know what is going on?'' asked the <PERSON>Pakistan-born
Khan</PERSON>, who took such a test when he became a naturalized citizen.
   Less than half the students knew that the supreme law of the
land is the Constitution.
   When asked what kind of government the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has, many
answered ``capitalist,'' rather than a democracy.
   Some said the pilgrims left <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> because they were searching
for something to colonize, apparently forgetting the religious
persecution that prompted them to flee to the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>.
   A decade ago, Khan gave a similar test of 10 questions to 118
students. Six passed.
   ``It's not getting any better,'' he said.
   It may be good for a few snickers when a student identifies
<PERSON>Abraham Lincoln</PERSON> as the principal author of the Declaration of
Independence, but when only one student answers 29 of the 30
questions correctly and just 18 get <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT> right, everybody
should be concerned, <PERSON>Khan</PERSON> said.
   ``I think people should know what is going on in this country,''
he said. ``We really do need a course in remedial <ORGANIZATION>American
Government</ORGANIZATION>.''
   For the record:
   _ The Pinta, not the <PERSON>Pinto</PERSON>, was one of three ships used by
<PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON>, along with the <PERSON>Nina</PERSON> and the <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>. The
pilgrims sailed in the <ORGANIZATION>Mayflower</ORGANIZATION>.
   _ <PERSON>Francis Scott Key</PERSON> wrote the national anthem, while <PERSON>Paul Revere</PERSON>
warned American revolutionaries the British were coming.
   _ <PERSON>Ms. O'Connor</PERSON> is the first woman to serve on the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION>,
which has yet to have a woman chief justice.
   _ <PERSON>Patrick Henry</PERSON> preferred death over tyranny in his famous to
the <LOCATION>Virginia House of Burgesses</LOCATION>, while <ORGANIZATION>MacArthur</ORGANIZATION> is remembered for
pledging ``I shall return'' to the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> and civil-rights
leader King for his ``I have a dream'' speech.
</TEXT>
