<DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; CITY; SPAIN; WORLD; HISTORY; FESTIVAL; NORTH-AMERICA; FOUND  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE 1992 Expo will be a major test for Seville, the capital of Andalusia and a
city infamous for its street crimes against tourists. It will be interesting
to see if the city can put a lid on the thousands of pickpockets, petty
thieves and moped-driving armed robbers that make being a tourist here so
exciting -- and also to see if anybody dies from the oven-hot weather that
hits around these parts in the summer.;    The Expo will be on a big island in
the middle of the Quadalquivar River, which runs through Seville. The river
once was a major artery for Americas-bound explorers.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SPAIN BETS A BUNDLE ON THE SUCCESS OF EXPO
'92  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Great Columbus Chase
Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.
See also related story on P. 1T of this section
Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     During <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>'s age of discovery -- and before the <LOCATION>Quadalquivar River</LOCATION> silted
up -- <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> was the headquarters for European trade with the New World, by
decree of <LOCATION>Ferdinand</LOCATION> and Isabella.;    <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> has other claims to fame. It's
the flamenco capital of the world. The cigar factory where <PERSON>Bizet</PERSON>'s <PERSON>Carmen</PERSON> did
her thing is here, and it's also the setting for two other famous operas --
"The Marriage of Figaro" and "The Barber of <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>." <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> is building an
opera house for these and other offerings. The new <ORGANIZATION>Teatro de la Maestranza</ORGANIZATION> is
supposed to be ready by <DATE>May</DATE>, with Spanish tenor <ORGANIZATION>Placido Domingo</ORGANIZATION> as operatic
director.;    And one of the most important collections of historical
documents in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> is found here, the <ORGANIZATION>Indies Archives</ORGANIZATION>, housed in a building
near the cathedral. The collection -- with nearly 50,000 files -- includes
maps, charts and letters from <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Magellan</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Cortes</PERSON> and other great
Spanish explorers. One of the goals of the Spanish government this year and
next is to computerize the files.;    Tourists planning to stop in on the
world's fair will find rooms hard to come by. <PERSON>Emilio Casinello</PERSON>, who's in
charge of the Expo, says some visitors might have to stay two or three hours
outside of town, but there will be rooms for everyone.;    The fair runs from
<DATE>April 20</DATE> to <DATE>Oct. 12</DATE>, and more than 100 countries are expected to participate.
The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Congress</ORGANIZATION> has appropriated <MONEY>$13 million</MONEY> for the <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> fair and
another <MONEY>$1.5 million</MONEY> for another <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> celebration to be held next <DATE>summer</DATE>
in <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Italy.</LOCATION>;    Monastery restored;  The Expo site -- La Cartuja island
in the <LOCATION>Quadalquivar River</LOCATION> -- covers about 530 acres. The 15th-century
monastery of <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION> de las Cuevas, once the only building on island, is
being restored, and its outer lodge will become a royal pavilion where <PERSON>King
Juan Carlos</PERSON> will receive visiting dignitaries. Columbus supposedly lived at
the monastery for eight years.;    The biggest foreign pavilions will be those
of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> hopes the
Expo will attract about 20 million visitors during its six-month run, half of
those foreigners. <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>, the same size as <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, is the smallest city
ever to host a world's fair.;    Like <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> is a city under siege
by construction workers. Spanish government investment now totals about <MONEY>$1.5
billion</MONEY> on the actual Expo site, with <MONEY>$7 billion</MONEY> more being spent on roads,
rail and other infrastructure.;    Twenty new hotels are under way, and by
next <DATE>spring</DATE>, officials are forecasting a total of 75,000 beds (current hotel
capacity in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> is about 10,000). Another 100,000 beds will be offered in
homes and apartments within an hour and a half of the city, and 600,000 more
beds are two and a half hours away on the <LOCATION>Costa</LOCATION> del Sol.;    Officials in
<LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> say they plan to ask local citizens to rent out their extra bedrooms
as part of a bed-and-breakfast program. Information about such programs should
be available from the <ORGANIZATION>Spanish National Tourist Office</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION>, but
calls there often result in "we don't know" responses.;    New rail service; 
Also by next <DATE>April</DATE>, <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> hopes to begin high-speed rail service between
<LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> using trains that will cut the journey from six hours to
two hours and 45 minutes. The service, to be known as AVE, after its Spanish
name, <ORGANIZATION>Tren de Alta Velocidad Espa</ORGANIZATION> ola, will travel at up to 186 miles an hour.
There will be an <ORGANIZATION>AVE</ORGANIZATION> terminal at the Expo site.;    The high-speed trains will
have air-conditioned cars and a cafe car with telephones and a boutique.
Between 10 and 14 daily departures in each direction are planned, but
schedules and fares have yet to be announced. And work is proceeding on a new
airport terminal that is hoped to triple passenger capacity.;    Also next
year, an antique train, the <ORGANIZATION>Andalusian Express</ORGANIZATION>, will begin service that
includes a trip from <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> on the AVE plus the train's normal
<DATE>summer</DATE> run from <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Cordoba</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Granada</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Malaga</LOCATION> and back to Seville.;  
 The Expo might make or break <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>. Andalusia in general -- and <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> in
particular -- are in bad economic shape. Spanish officials hope the fair will
attract future investments to the city and the province -- hence the big money
being put into fixing up the infrastructure.;     IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; For
general information about <LOCATION>Andalusia</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> region, contact the
<ORGANIZATION>Spanish National Tourist Office</ORGANIZATION>, 8383 <LOCATION>Wilshire Blvd.</LOCATION>, No. 960, <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION>
90211; (213) 658-7188. Among events planned for next year are:;    (check)
<LOCATION>COLOMBO</LOCATION> '92 -- <LOCATION>Genoa</LOCATION>, <DATE>May 15-Aug</DATE>. 15. Another Expo, this one concentrating on
maritime activities and on <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> himself.;    (check) GRAND REGATTA
<LOCATION>COLUMBUS</LOCATION> '92 -- <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>, <DATE>May-June 1992</DATE>. A fleet of tall sailing ships and
hundreds of pleasure craft will sail from <LOCATION>Cadiz</LOCATION> and arrive at <LOCATION>San Juan</LOCATION> in <DATE>May
1992</DATE>. There will be events in <LOCATION>San Juan June 10-14.</LOCATION>;    (check) <DATE>1992</DATE> SUMMER
OLYMPICS -- <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION>, <DATE>July 25-Aug</DATE>. 9, <DATE>1992</DATE>. The games are dedicated to
Columbus.;     If you go . . .; (check) Expo Factos -- The <DATE>1992</DATE> world's fair
will stay open late -- probably <TIME>4 a.m.</TIME> -- to cope with <DATE>July</DATE> temperatures that
often soar above 100 degrees. A one-day ticket is about <MONEY>$40</MONEY> per person.;   
Visitors may enter and leave the site any time between <TIME>9 a.m.</TIME> and <TIME>4 p.m.</TIME>
Pavilions will be open from <TIME>10 a.m. to 10 p.m</TIME>. A night-time ticket for <MONEY>$10</MONEY>
will allow entry from <TIME>8 p.m.</TIME> to <TIME>4 a.m.</TIME> Evening activities include a parade,
laser and fireworks display over the Expo lake, concerts, theater, dance
programs, cinema programs, discos and night clubs.;    Many attractions and
pavilions will focus on progress. Included among facilities on the island will
be a monorail to take visitors around the exhibition, and a cable car linking
the fair site with the city. Fair officials plan to plant 350,000 trees and
bushes and 30 miles of hedge to create a screen of vegetation against the
fierce heat.;    (check) <LOCATION>COLUMBUS</LOCATION> TRACKING -- If you want to see the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
crypt, go to the vast Gothic cathedral in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>, which holds the ornate tomb
built to hold <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' remains. The cathedral is said to be the third largest
in the world. (<ORGANIZATION>St. Peter</ORGANIZATION>'s in <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>St. Paul</LOCATION>'s in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> are one and two.)
Another <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> spot is the so-called Tower of Gold, the point on the river
from where <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> sailed on his later trips to the Americas.;    (check)
INFORMATION -- <ORGANIZATION>Spanish National Tourist Office</ORGANIZATION>, 8383 <LOCATION>Wilshire Blvd.</LOCATION>, No. 960,
<LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION> 90211; (213) 658-7188.;    (check) PACKAGE TOURS -- Some package
tours to the Expo include some Columbus-tracking, including trips to <ORGANIZATION>Palos de
la Frontera</ORGANIZATION>, the monastery at La Rabida and the <LOCATION>Azores</LOCATION>. Some itineraries also
include Genoa.;    (box)  4th Dimension Tours (800) 343-0020 or (305)
477-1525); and <PERSON>Marsans</PERSON> International (800) 223-6114 or (212) 239-3880) have
scheduled "Footsteps of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" tours, but they currently are being offered
to pre-formed groups only.;    (box)  Cruises with a <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> theme generally
will sail to islands in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> on which the explorer himself set foot
on his New-World voyages -- particularly <LOCATION>San Salvador</LOCATION> in the <LOCATION>Bahamas.</LOCATION>;    Some
choices for this type of cruise are American Canadian Caribbean Line, (800)
556-7450 or (401) 247-0955); Costa Cruises, (800) 462-6782 or (305) 358-7325);
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> Jubilee Cruises, (800-HOT-1992).;    (box) For more information about
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, try these books:;    (check) "The Conquest of Paradise" by
<ORGANIZATION>Kirkpatrick Sale</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Knopf</ORGANIZATION>, <MONEY>$24.95</MONEY>).;    (check) "Christopher Columbus" by <PERSON>Gianni
Granzotto</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>University of Oklahoma Press</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>1984</DATE>).;    (check) "Columbus: His
Enterprise" by <PERSON>Hans Konig</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>Monthly Review Press</ORGANIZATION>), <MONEY>$8.95</MONEY>.;    (check) "Admiral
of the Open Sea," <PERSON>Samuel Eliot Morison</PERSON> (Little <PERSON>Brown</PERSON> and Company, <DATE>1949</DATE>).  </TEXT>
