<CAPTION>  Drawings (2); DRAWING: Indians having their hands chopped off for failing to
meet the gold dust quota. From the book 'Spanish Cruelties,' published in 1609
with engravings by Bartolome de las Casas, who accompanied Columbus on his
first voyages to the Americas. (color); DRAWING: (Columbus) (color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HISTORY; FOUND; NORTH-AMERICA; FESTIVAL; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE year is 1492.;    The place, a lush Caribbean paradise -- the ground
littered with hands chopped off at the wrists.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE GREAT COLUMBUS CHASE
IT'S 'NOT MY PARTY': STORM BREWS OVER '92
CELEBRATION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
See also related stories on P. 1T, 7T, 8T, 9T and 10T of this section
The Great Columbus Chase  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Arawak men, women and children stumble away, blood gushing from stumps --
in punishment for failing to meet the impossible gold-dust quotas of
<PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON> and his crew.;    It is the beginning of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'
voyages to the Americas. And this unholy scene, repeated on later journeys, is
spun from <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>'s lust for gold and the Spanish desire for Christian
converts. This is the Eden-turned-hell that <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> misnames "the New
World.";    But in reality, it is an ancient, well-populated world. What
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> did not find in gold or converts, say some historians and social
critics, he made up for in blood: the enslavement and murder of the Taino and
Arawak peoples.;    "The historical facts are on record," says <PERSON>Hans Koning</PERSON>,
author of "Columbus: His Enterprise." "We've told our children he was a great
hero -- that's total hokum pokum. Columbus was not a force for the good. If an
entire race stood in his way, it had to go.";    This increasingly negative
reassessment of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> is igniting a passionate international controversy
over the <DATE>1992</DATE> celebration of the 500th anniversary of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> voyage.;   
To celebrate the anniversary, a presidential commission was created by
<ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1984</DATE> to coordinate activities in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and cooperate
with European planners. The organization -- the <ORGANIZATION>Quincentenary Jubilee
Commission</ORGANIZATION> -- drew fire from the beginning because no Indians were included on
the 30-member commission. There are four Hispanics, one African-American and
10 Italian-Americans on the panel.;    <ORGANIZATION>Commission</ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON>James Kuhn</PERSON>
downplays the question of the panel's racial makeup, saying, "We don't think
of it in these terms.";    But there are many critics who do. "Where's the
native point of view?" asks <PERSON>LaDonna Harris</PERSON>, a Comanche and founder of
Americans for Indian Opportunity in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION>;    Meanwhile, on both
sides of the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>, officials and hawkers are planning parties, media
events and T-shirt sales. Replicas of the <ORGANIZATION>Nina</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Pinta</ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>
will be displayed in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> in <DATE>October 1992</DATE>, after touring other
cities.;    "And guess what flag they'll be flying -- the <ORGANIZATION>Texaco</ORGANIZATION> flag," says
<PERSON>Roberto Ramirez</PERSON> of the <LOCATION>South Bay</LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION>Quincentennial Indigenous Council</ORGANIZATION>. "This
commercialization represents the mentality behind the official celebration."; 
  For <PERSON>Ramirez</PERSON> and others, <DATE>1992</DATE> is the remembrance of a holocaust in which
people were raped, tortured and killed. All for the sake of gold that wasn't
there and a religion that converted not a single Indian.;    "Five hundred
years of genocide is not a cause for celebration," says <PERSON>Charley Trujillo</PERSON>, a
San Jose publisher, author and historian. "We're supposed to celebrate a
holocaust? It's unthinkable.";    "It's like asking the world to celebrate
<PERSON>Hitler</PERSON>'s holocaust of the Jewish people," says <PERSON>Rosemary Richmond</PERSON>, of the
<ORGANIZATION>American Indian Community House</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. "I am an American Indian; this is
not my party.";    In response to increasing objection to the term
"celebration," <PERSON>Kuhn</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Jubilee Commission</ORGANIZATION> has said: "We don't call it a
celebration. We call it a commemoration.";    But critics still say things
smack of a celebration. For them, <DATE>1992</DATE> is instead a time to protest, to mourn,
to educate.;    "What must be done in <DATE>1992</DATE>," says <PERSON>Carlos Munoz</PERSON>, a UC-Berkeley
professor of political history, "is writing letters to the editor, protesting
official <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> events, alerting educators and commemorating the original
Americans in an alternative historical perspective.";    Welcome to the
alternative quincentennial movement and its growing thunder, as it rumbles
across all borders of race, religion and rank. For starters:;    (check) In
<LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, the mayor of <LOCATION>Cadiz</LOCATION> has donated land for a monument to the victims of
European conquerors.;    (check) In <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>, the <DATE>1991</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Fourth Havana Biennial</ORGANIZATION> has
declared a "Challenge to Colonization.";    (check) At <ORGANIZATION>Stanford University</ORGANIZATION>,
artist-writer <PERSON>Jose Antonio Burciaga</PERSON> is distributing <PERSON>Koning</PERSON>'s book as "chain"
gifts to be passed on every two weeks: "People need to know what happened in
<DATE>1492</DATE> so they can figure what to do in <DATE>1992</DATE>.";    (check) And from the Submuloc
Society (<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> spelled backward) at <ORGANIZATION>Salish Kootenai College</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Pablo</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Mont.</LOCATION>, the movement has a T-shirt: three ships within a circle crossed by a
diagonal line -- the international symbol for "not allowed.";   
Demonstrations began last year when activists, including Indian leader <PERSON>Russell
Means</PERSON>, protested a traveling <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> exhibit called "First Encounters,"
created by the <ORGANIZATION>Florida Museum of Natural History.</ORGANIZATION>;    "The exhibit should have
shown colonialism at work," says protest organizer <PERSON>Jan Elliott</PERSON> of the
<ORGANIZATION>Committee for American Indian History</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Gainesville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>;    An Indian
demonstrator was accused of "spoiling our children's fun." But, says <PERSON>Koning</PERSON>,
who was there, 'It's not innocent pleasure to celebrate an appalling
history.";    In response, the <ORGANIZATION>Houston Museum of Natural Science</ORGANIZATION> has canceled
the exhibit. Its next stop is the <ORGANIZATION>Southwest Museum of Science and Technology</ORGANIZATION>
in <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> on <DATE>Sept. 26</DATE>, where a protest will be staged <DATE>Oct. 12</DATE> by <PERSON>Elliott</PERSON>'s
coalition.;    "If people ask, 'What have you got against <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>?' -- they
don't know about the lie of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>," says <PERSON>Elliott</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Cherokee Creole</ORGANIZATION> and
Ph.D candidate in Indian philosophy.;    But no protests are planned for the
Science Museum of <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>St. Paul</LOCATION>. Its curator of ethnology, <PERSON>Dan Swan</PERSON>,
is working closely with Indians to illuminate the exhibit's eurocentrism and
to offer a multicultural perspective.;    Similarly in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Jorge
Gonzales</PERSON> is part of <LOCATION>Santa Clara County</LOCATION>'s multiethnic, multiracial commission
to develop a multicultural response. "An objective is to include the
indigenous perspective," <PERSON>Gonzales</PERSON> says.;    <PERSON>Gonzales</PERSON> is a member of <ORGANIZATION>Raza Si</ORGANIZATION>,
an immigrant-rights advocacy organization, and the <LOCATION>South Bay</LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION>Quincentennial
Indigenous Council</ORGANIZATION>. On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> the council will have a traditional Indian
feast, open to the public, at Mother <PERSON>Olson</PERSON>'s Inn in <LOCATION>San Jose.</LOCATION>;    "Native
people are taking a stand," says <PERSON>Norma Sanchez</PERSON> of the <PERSON>Muwekma-Ohlone Tribe</PERSON>,
who estimates 16,000 Indians live in <LOCATION>Santa Clara County</LOCATION>. "We will not
celebrate colonialism, but we will help people gain new understanding.";   
About 10,000 Ohlones live in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, according to <PERSON>Rosemary Cambra</PERSON>
of the <ORGANIZATION>Muwekma-Ohlone Tribe</ORGANIZATION>. "<ORGANIZATION>Hayward State University</ORGANIZATION> and UC-Berkeley are
planning Ohlone exhibits as part of an alternative response," she reports.;   
Likewise, <PERSON>Hugh Wire</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Council of Churches</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Santa Clara County</LOCATION> says, "In
<DATE>1992</DATE>, we'll work toward a restoration of Native American pride.";    From <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>National Council of Churches</ORGANIZATION> calls the Jubilee a legitimization "of
racial oppression" and vows to protest it through observances and events
across the nation.;    In cities where the indigenous perspective is ignored,
activists plan demonstrations through <DATE>1992</DATE>. "We may greet the ships in <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION> naked with our feathers and rubber-tipped bows and arrows," <PERSON>Elliott</PERSON>
says.;    In <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Solidarity Foundation</ORGANIZATION> plans a festival in <LOCATION>Central
Park</LOCATION> to counter the arrival of the tall ships in the harbor.;    Another
target is <LOCATION>Columbus Day</LOCATION>, <DATE>Oct. 12</DATE>. Indians object to glorifying a man they call
a false hero. The <DATE>1992</DATE> Alliance in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION>, plans a sunrise ceremony
this <ORGANIZATION>Columbus Day</ORGANIZATION> in front of the capitol.;    "We're declaring <DATE>1992</DATE> the Year
of the Indigenous People," says <PERSON>Suzan Harjo</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Cheyenne</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Creek Indian and
Alliance</ORGANIZATION> national coordinator. "We'll remember those who didn't survive the
European invasion; we'll celebrate those who have survived.";    Others are
declaring <DATE>Oct. 13</DATE> a Day of Mourning. Still others are calling for a moment to
an hour of silence on <DATE>Oct. 12</DATE>. Another plan is to celebrate <DATE>Oct. 11</DATE> as <ORGANIZATION>Native
People</ORGANIZATION>'s <DATE>Last Day</DATE> of Freedom.;    Last year, the <ORGANIZATION>American Indian Movement</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION> protested <ORGANIZATION>Columbus Day</ORGANIZATION> and unveiled an effigy of Hitler next to
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' statue. Elliott's group will continue protesting a planned <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY>
Columbus statue in <LOCATION>Corpus Christi</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas.</LOCATION>;    Writer <PERSON>Jack Weatherford</PERSON> proposes
abolishing <ORGANIZATION>Columbus Day</ORGANIZATION>. Why honor a man "who opened the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> slave trade
and launched one of the greatest waves of genocide known in history?" he
writes.;    "This gathering storm has already made an impact," says
<PERSON>Kirkpatrick Sale</PERSON>, author of "The Conquest of Paradise." "That's why the
national celebration is failing to get off the ground. There's an awareness
that celebration is not a moral response to <DATE>1992</DATE>.";    A moral response is the
counter-movement's call to action.;    Already there are plans for educational
conferences. Sale attended such a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>National Society of Social
Studies Teachers</ORGANIZATION>. "To their credit," he says, "they're perplexed over how to
present the quincentenary to students. They realize a celebration is
inappropriate.";    Also at issue is the grade school notion of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
'discovering' <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>. Elliott calls it "the myth of an empty continent.";   
"Colon did not discover it," Sale writes. It was "well-known to the millions
of people . . . who had discovered (it) on behalf of the human species tens of
thousands of years before.";    Apologists for the "discovery" notion excuse
the term because the land was new to <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>. But <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION> says, "If I step
off a ship in <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, I do not 'discover' it, even if it's 'new' to me.";   
Eurocentric racism feeds this myth, says <PERSON>Peter McDonald</PERSON>, former Native
American Indian bibliographer at <ORGANIZATION>New York Public Library</ORGANIZATION>, now with <ORGANIZATION>Cornell
University</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Northeast Indian Quarterly.</ORGANIZATION>;    "The idea of a white person
'discovering' a continent -- already populated from sea to shining sea -- is
absurd," <ORGANIZATION>McDonald</ORGANIZATION> says. "The Incas, the Aztecs had astronomy, engineering,
mathematics, hygiene, an agriculture far in advance of anything in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>.";  
 The myth of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, he adds, "numbs us to the truth of how this continent
was stolen in a ruthless expanse, leaving a trail of broken promises leading
up to today.";    In response to such criticism, Jubilee commissioner <PERSON>Kuhn</PERSON> has
said: "I may have said discovery in the past, but now I refer to it as an
encounter.";    "Calling it an 'encounter' is an attempt to hoodwink people,"
<ORGANIZATION>McDonald</ORGANIZATION> says. "Raping, murdering, enslaving people is hardly an 'encounter'
of two cultures.";    Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION>Hollywood</ORGANIZATION> is producing two <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> films,
one written by <PERSON>Mario Puzo</PERSON> and the other directed by <PERSON>Ridley Scott</PERSON>. Activists
don't expect either to tell the true tale of <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON>. However,
<PERSON>Koning</PERSON> says, "Actor <PERSON>Tim Robbins</PERSON> has written a play based on my book, and he
hopes to talk to <PERSON>Ridley Scott</PERSON> about it.";    Whatever happens during the next
year and a half, Sale says, "when <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> is talked about from now on, it
will be with a greater awareness.";    <PERSON>Adds Koning</PERSON>, "It may seem a pity to let
go of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> as part of our national lore, but we cannot in good faith
celebrate this man nor the quincentenary. False heroes have too long burdened
our history. If people really want to do something in <DATE>1992</DATE>, tell them to talk
with a Native American.";    It's a good idea, says <PERSON>June LeGrand</PERSON>, radio host
for "The Living Spirit" on KKUP-FM and co-founder of the <LOCATION>South Bay
Quincentennial Indigenous Council.</LOCATION>;    "We've been invisible for so long.
Until the world heals its relationship to Indian people, there can be no
harmony on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. <DATE>1992</DATE> offers us a chance to finally meet all of our brothers
and sisters."  </TEXT>
