<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: 'Crown of Columbus' is the first novel Erdrich and Dorris wrote
together  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  BOOK; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE CROWN OF COLUMBUS; By Michael Dorris and Louise Erdrich  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COLUMBIAN COLLABORATION
LOUISE ERDRICH, MICHAEL DORRIS CREATE A WONDERFUL
TREASURE HUNT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Books
Giles, a regular reviewer for the Mercury News, teaches writing at San
Francisco State University. She is this year's winner of the reviewing
citation from the National Book Critics Circle.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  HarperCollins, 384 pp., <MONEY>$21.95</MONEY>;  THERE has already been a lot of hype about
"The Crown of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>," and there is probably going to be a lot more. The
novel sold for an enormous amount of money (the advance alone was an
unprecedented three-quarters of a <MONEY>million dollars</MONEY>). The <ORGANIZATION>Book-of-the-Month Club</ORGANIZATION>
has bid on it, so have the magazines and translators; <PERSON>Michelle Pfeiffer</PERSON> owns
the movie rights.;    The authors, <PERSON>Michael Dorris</PERSON> and <PERSON>Louise Erdrich</PERSON>, are
already on a national publicity tour. Handsome and appealing, they make fine
spokespeople for their own work and provide unusually interesting copy for
articles and interviews. Both are of mixed American Indian descent, and both
grew up, at least partly, on reservations. They have been married 10 years and
are raising six children together. Prize-winning authors on their own
(<ORGANIZATION>Erdrich</ORGANIZATION>'s "Love Medicine" won the <ORGANIZATION>National Book Critics Circle Award</ORGANIZATION> for
Fiction in <DATE>1984</DATE>, and <PERSON>Dorris</PERSON>' "The Broken Cord" won the <ORGANIZATION>National Book Critics
Circle Award</ORGANIZATION> for Non-Fiction in <DATE>1989</DATE>), the two are used to reading and
commenting on each other's work, but they have never openly collaborated on a
full-length book before.;    And the book? Well, it's great. "The Crown of
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" feels exactly like the family-written book it is. Unpretentious and
engaging, it has more charm and humor than readers may have found in earlier
<PERSON>Dorris</PERSON> and/or <PERSON>Erdrich</PERSON> works, without sacrificing any of the intelligence or
feeling. The very first sentence ("In the warm pink-gold of a <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>
afternoon, something marvelous washed up from the sea") sets the tone, and
this light and literate quality lasts throughout the book.;    The plot
focuses on the on-again, off-again romance between two very different
<LOCATION>Dartmouth</LOCATION> professors as they try to second-guess <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON> -- who
he was, what he wanted, what his legacy to <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> really consisted of.;   
<PERSON>Vivian Twostar</PERSON>, who narrates part of the book, is a spunky, outspoken
40-year-old single mother who teaches American Indian studies in the
anthropology department. Forced by the requirements of her tenure year to
write an article on <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>, whom she refers to sarcastically as "<PERSON>Mr.
Navigator</PERSON>," <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON> begins her research with reluctance. She wants what every
"other sensible person of full or partial American Indian descent" wants --
that is, she wants to nail him.;    <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON> has a clear idea of what life was
like for her people before <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> landed. The Indians on the tiny island of
<LOCATION>Guanahani</LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION>, were, she tells us, "a healthy pleasure-loving
group, laid-back beach bums and surfers, with absolutely no aptitude for
destruction." They lived in "an endless <DATE>summer</DATE> of surf and starry nights"
until, in <DATE>1492</DATE>, the fateful sails of the <ORGANIZATION>Nina</ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION>Pinta</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Santa Maria</LOCATION>
appeared on the horizon. Then, Vivian fumes, they all ran down to meet the
ships -- they had, after all, no reason to think the Spaniards weren't simply
bringing "more good news.";    <PERSON>Roger Williams</PERSON>, an elegant, emotionally inept
academician who talks to students and fellow professors using the "odd,
two-fingered hand position Christ used in <LOCATION>Bible</LOCATION> story illustrations," is
writing about <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> for different reasons: He is interested in the man as
an Italian who sailed for <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, a Jew who converted to Christianity, a
navigator who never found the "Orient" he aimed for. Roger, a narrative poet,
is writing an unrhymed monologue titled "Diary of a Lost Man" that starts with
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' admission: "I do not know myself.";    The two, <PERSON>Roger</PERSON> and <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>,
have a comic confrontation in the <LOCATION>Dartmouth</LOCATION> library when <PERSON>Roger</PERSON>'s cough alerts
<PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>'s anger. "The first European who stood on the North American continent
and coughed," <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON> remembers, "probably indirectly killed more Indians than
. . . <PERSON>Custer</PERSON> ever imagined in his favorite wet dream." They fall in love, but
break apart when <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON> learns she is pregnant. They stay apart until <PERSON>Roger</PERSON>
learns to develop "a tolerance for change" that includes accepting <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>, her
teen-age son <PERSON>Nash</PERSON> ("just spell it G-N-A-S-H"), her irritable Navajo
grandmother and their new baby, Violet -- the "whole unruly entourage.";    In
the meantime, both continue to track down information on <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>. They agree
on one fact: <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> was a slave trader. The gold he failed to find in the
New World he supplanted with natives he bragged would make "good and
intelligent servants" for Spain.;    But what are these references to a
mysterious "crown" in the journals and notes? When a sinister millionaire
named <ORGANIZATION>Cobb</ORGANIZATION> offers to help put the pieces together, <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>, <PERSON>Roger</PERSON>, <PERSON>Nash</PERSON> and the
baby fly to his mansion in the <LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION>. Roger sees nothing but fleas and
mosquitoes on the tropical island, and <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>'s view is also bleak: The "poor
soil, bright colors, dark people, junked automobiles" all remind her of a
reservation. Cobb's private beach is, however, the promised paradise. And as
<ORGANIZATION>Cobb</ORGANIZATION>'s clues tally with <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>'s, the race to find the "real" <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> speeds
up.;     "The Crown of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" is an old-fashioned treasure-hunt story that
offers a little bit for everyone -- there are bats, sharks, caves,
kidnappings, codes and karate chops, as well as poems by <PERSON>Donne</PERSON> and <PERSON>Roger
Williams</PERSON>, entries from <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' diary, Navajo chants and wonderful
descriptions of university librarians, childbirth and stoned 16-year-old boys.
The only thing missing is the recipe for <PERSON>Vivian</PERSON>'s chili.;     There are, to be
sure, some flat parts and some thin characters. Columbus himself remains sadly
elusive. There is a <ORGANIZATION>Nancy Drew-gets-together-with-the-Hardy-Boys</ORGANIZATION> quality that
may put off the sophisticated. But the good spirit of the book is contagious,
and that, essentially, is what makes it so effective.;    "The Crown of
<LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>" feels as if it was written in fun, conceived and constructed in an
atmosphere of camaraderie, respect and good faith. If only <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> had landed
on our shores with half these qualities . . .  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  MOLLY GILES  </BYLINE>
