<HL> International: Spain to Celebrate Columbus's Voyage At an $800 Million Coming-Out Party </HL>
<AUTHOR> Nicholas Bray (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP </CO>
<DATELINE> SEVILLE, Spain  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> has begun restoring the <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> monastery where <PERSON>Christopher Columbus</PERSON> rested between sailings, and where he lay buried for a quarter century after he died, as part of an <MONEY>$800 million</MONEY> extravaganza to commemorate his discovery of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>. 

   But Expo <DATE>'92</DATE>, as the project is called, will be more than just a celebration of the 500th anniversary of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s voyage to the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>. 
It will also be an international coming-out party for <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>'s emergence as a modern democracy. 

   Falling nearly two decades after the death in <DATE>1975</DATE> of right-wing dictator Gen. <PERSON>Francisco Franco</PERSON>, <DATE>1992</DATE> is the final year before <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>'s full integration into the <ORGANIZATION>European Community</ORGANIZATION> and also the year of the <LOCATION>Barcelona</LOCATION> Olympics. 
In addition, <DATE>1992</DATE> is the year the <ORGANIZATION>EC</ORGANIZATION> is supposed to dismantle all remaining trade barriers within its borders -- a major test for Spanish industry, which is modernizing but still shackled by a history of state paternalism and protectionism. 

   "It can reinforce the idea <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> is regaining a position within the Western community, that it isn't a Third World country but one that also has some cards to play," says <PERSON>Juan Diez Nicolas</PERSON>, a sociologist. 

   The exposition in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> will run from <DATE>April</DATE> until <DATE>Oct. 12</DATE> -- 500 years to the day from <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>'s landing on the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> island of <LOCATION>San Salvador</LOCATION>. 
It is expected to attract 20 million visitors. 

   The budget of more than <MONEY>$800 million</MONEY> is to be covered by entry charges, the sale of television and souvenir rights, and sponsorship by commercial firms. 
Like the <DATE>1984</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Los Angeles Olympics</ORGANIZATION>, Expo '92 is supposed to pay for itself. 

   There are doubters: <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>, a city of 700,000, is better known for flamenco dancing and music and bullfights than for science and high technology -- the themes of the exposition. 
How much public interest it will generate isn't evident, even to some Spaniards. 
"I really don't know whether the exhibition has a clear enough theme to arouse much enthusiasm," comments a <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> businessman. 

   The former Carthusian monastery where <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> often stayed and where he was buried from <DATE>1509</DATE> until his body was moved to <ORGANIZATION>Santo Domingo</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1536</DATE>, will be the centerpiece of Expo <DATE>'92</DATE>. 
Converted into a ceramics factory in the <DATE>early 19th century</DATE> and vacant since <DATE>1982</DATE>, it is being rebuilt as an architectural showcase. 
King <PERSON>Juan Carlos</PERSON>, hailed in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> as a national savior for thwarting an attempted military coup in <DATE>1981</DATE>, will spend much of his time there welcoming foreign leaders. 

   More than 70 nations, including all of <LOCATION>Latin America</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and most European nations, have already said they will take part in Expo <DATE>'92</DATE>. 
<PERSON>Manuel Olivencia</PERSON>, a law professor who is the exposition's government-appointed director, wants to beat the record set in <LOCATION>Osaka</LOCATION>, when 77 nations took part. 

   In the buildup to <DATE>1992</DATE>, about <MONEY>500 billion pesetas</MONEY> (<MONEY>$4.2 billion</MONEY>) is being spent on such major public-works projects as a high-speed train link with <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>, highways and improved airport facilities. 
Some 200,000 jobs are expected to be created, and in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION> real-estate prices have more than quintupled in the formerly depressed area along the <LOCATION>Guadalquivir River</LOCATION> overlooking the exhibition site. 

   Four Spanish banks have agreed to provide <MONEY>$67 million</MONEY> for rights to the Expo '92 logo and mascot. 
Multinational companies like <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Alcatel N.V.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Siemens AG</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>N.V. Philips</ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION>Netherlands</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Xerox Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> are paying <MONEY>$8.2 million</MONEY> to act as official sponsors. 

   In hopes of avoiding a debacle, planners have studied other world expositions, including the money-losing <DATE>1967</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Montreal Expo</ORGANIZATION>, and some smaller international expositions such as those in <LOCATION>Tsukuba</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> in <DATE>1985</DATE> and in <LOCATION>Vancouver</LOCATION> in <DATE>1986</DATE>. 

   Expo director <PERSON>Olivencia</PERSON> acknowledges the challenge he faces. 
Success or failure in <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>, he says, is likely to be crucial for similar projects planned by other nations between <DATE>1992</DATE> and <DATE>2001</DATE>. 

   <LOCATION>Vienna</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> have proposed a joint international exposition in <DATE>1995</DATE> to commemorate, among other things, the 50th anniversary of the end of World War II and the 40th anniversary of <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>'s restored independence. 
In <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>, businessmen have proposed an exposition in <DATE>1997</DATE>, the year <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> is to hand back the colony to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. 
<LOCATION>Hanover</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, is bidding to hold a world's fair in <DATE>1998</DATE> or <DATE>2000</DATE>, and there are rumors of other bids from <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Venice</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Oslo</LOCATION>. 

   After a period when many people thought the era of such extravaganzas was over, "there has been a resurgence of interest," says <PERSON>Marie-Helene Defrene</PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION>International Expositions Bureau</ORGANIZATION>, an inter-governmental agency based in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>
