<HEAD>Commission Faces Probe, Search for New Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Monday correct in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financially troubled presidential commission
planning the 500th anniversary celebration of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' <DATE>1492</DATE> voyage
to <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> faces a congressional investigation and a search for a
new chairman.
   <PERSON>John Goudie</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> resigned <DATE>Monday</DATE> as head of the <ORGANIZATION>Christopher
Columbus Quincentenary Jubilee Commission</ORGANIZATION> out of what his deputy
said was a sense of frustration.
   <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON> was a fund-raiser for the unsuccessful re-election effort
of <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON>Bob Martinez</PERSON>, who is President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s nominee as
director of national drug control policy. He was appointed to the
commission by former President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>.
   The commission is <MONEY>$600,000</MONEY> in arrears on an agreement to pay
<LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> for replicas of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' three ships. The ships are to tour
American ports for the celebration.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texaco Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, which has pledged <MONEY>$5 million</MONEY>, stopped its donations
in <DATE>September</DATE> because of ``some technical matters and overall
management of the program,'' <ORGANIZATION>Texaco</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>K. Peter Maneri</PERSON> said
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. He said the company hopes the problems, which he refused
to detail, can be worked out and financial support resumed.
   Another potential sponsor, <ORGANIZATION>Chrysler Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, says it wants to
clear up unspecified contractual questions before making a donation
of more than <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY>.
   A <ORGANIZATION>House Post Office and Civil Service</ORGANIZATION> subcommittee, meanwhile,
is delving into <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON>'s longtime friendship with <PERSON>Manuel Gonzalez</PERSON>,
a <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> businessmen who has been involved in plans for the
celebration.
   A businessman, <PERSON>Peter Dunev</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, paid <MONEY>$50,000</MONEY> for the right
to place the 500th anniversary logo on T-shirts. Gonzalez came by
<ORGANIZATION>Dunev</ORGANIZATION>'s office last <DATE>summer</DATE> to pick up the checks for the <MONEY>$50,000</MONEY>,
<PERSON>Dunev</PERSON> said in an interview.
   The checks were made out to <ORGANIZATION>Christopher Columbus Licensing Group
Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. The commission has awarded the
licensing group a contract enabling it to keep <PERCENT>85 percent</PERCENT> of
commission-related sales on T-shirts and souvenirs.
   <PERSON>Bill Rolen</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Knoxville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn.</LOCATION>, businessman who had made a
proposal for the celebration, said <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON> introduced him to
<PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> as a friend who might be able to provide <PERSON>Rolen</PERSON> with
financing
   <PERSON>Rolen</PERSON> said the two didn't do business because <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> wanted
part ownership in <ORGANIZATION>Rolen</ORGANIZATION>'s proposed venture. It was to have been a
renovation of a former world's fair exposition hall in <LOCATION>Knoxville</LOCATION>
for the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> celebration.
   Gonzalez did not return telephone calls to his home and office
in <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>. Goudie also couldn't be reached.
   However, the commission's deputy director, <PERSON>Jana Joustra</PERSON>, said
<PERSON>Goudie</PERSON>'s resignation from the non-salaried, part-time post was
``completely voluntary.'' She said <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON> ``got fed up'' with the
problems, the lack of financial support and the criticism he faced
after spending a great deal of his own time on the project.
   ``Nobody appreciated it,'' she said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> appropriates <MONEY>$212,000</MONEY> a year for the commission to pay
part of the salaries and rent for the six-member staff.
   The congressional subcommittee's investigation of the commission
will continue, said the panel's chairman, Rep. <PERSON>Thomas Sawyer</PERSON>,
<LOCATION>D-Ohio</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
