<HEAD>Report: Columbus Commission Under Financial Scrutiny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the presidential commission
organizing the 500th anniversary celebration of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>' voyage to
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION> says he has submitted his resignation amid questions about
his and the panel's finances.
   <PERSON>John Goudie</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> Republican and real estate businessman, was
quoted as saying in <ORGANIZATION>The New York Times</ORGANIZATION> today that he sent a letter
to President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> announcing his resignation from the unsalaried
post.
   <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON>, who was appointed by President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> in <DATE>1985</DATE>, denied
any wrongdoing.
   ``It's time for me to bow out,'' he said, adding that the
commision needed ``some favorable publicity.''
   There was no immediate word on whether <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON>'s resignation was
accepted. <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Sean Walsh</PERSON> had no comment on the
report.
   A <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> subcommittee has been looking at whether the <ORGANIZATION>Christopher
Columbus Quincentenary Jubilee Commission</ORGANIZATION> has awarded contracts
properly. Some of the arrangements under scrutiny involve friends
of <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON>'s, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The congressional panel plans to hold hearings next year into
the running of the commission after an audit by the <ORGANIZATION>General
Accounting Office</ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper said.
   The 5-year-old commission is <MONEY>$600,000</MONEY> behind on an agreement
with <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, which has built replicas of the three ships <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>
led to the <LOCATION>New World</LOCATION>, because <ORGANIZATION>Texaco Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a main sponsor, has
stopped its donations, the newspaper said.
   Texaco and <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON> said the money was halted because of a
contractual dispute.
   <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON> said he is resigning because publicity over the <ORGANIZATION>Texaco</ORGANIZATION>
incident has jeopardized a pledge from the <ORGANIZATION>Chrysler Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   One member of the commission, <PERSON>Virgil Dechant</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Hamden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn.</LOCATION>,
said he knew nothing of a resignation by <PERSON>Goudie</PERSON>. <PERSON>Dechant</PERSON> said that
to his knowledge, the commission had no particular financial
problems.
   Another member of the commission, <PERSON>Mary Jane Checci</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, also said she knew nothing of a resignation.
</TEXT>
